            <p>FURMAN SHEPPARD&#44;<lb/>
                Attorney at Law&#44;<lb/>
                No. 717 WALNUT STREET.<lb/></p>
            <p>PHILADELPHIA&#44; April 11&#44; 1890<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev Dr Morais<lb/></p>
            <p>My dear Sir<lb/></p>
            <p>A few days since I advertised in<lb/> the Public Ledger for a German lad for<lb/> my office and I received an answer from<lb/> J. Z. Josephson&#44; who named you as<lb/> a reference.  I thought I would like<lb/> to see the lad and wrote him requesting<lb/> him to call on me&#44; the letter being<lb/> addressed to him at the Post Office&#44; as<lb/> he suggested.  As I have not heard from<lb/> him&#44; my letter may in some way have<lb/> miscarried.  If you happen to know<lb/> his address&#44; and can recommend him&#44;<lb/> I have no objections to having an<lb/> interview with him&#44; if you can con&#45;<lb/>&#45;veniently get word to him to that<lb/> effect.  Hoping you will excuse the<lb/> liberty I take in requesting you to do<lb/> so&#44; I am<lb/> very Resply yrs<lb/> Furman Sheppard<lb/></p>
            </body>
    </text>
